# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iot-security-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A **botnet** is a group of Internet-connected devices, each of which runs one or more bots.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Botnets can be used to perform distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attacks, steal data, send spam, and allow the attacker to access the device and its connection.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The owner can control the botnet using command and control (C&C) software.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The word "botnet" is a portmanteau of the words "robot" and "network".
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The term is usually used with a negative or malicious connotation.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A botnet is a logical collection of Internet-connected devices, such as computers, smartphones or Internet of things (IoT) devices whose security have been breached and control ceded to a third party.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Each compromised device, known as a "bot," is created when a device is penetrated by software from a *malware* (malicious software) distribution.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The controller of a botnet can direct the activities of these compromised computers through communication channels formed by network protocols, such as Internet Relay Chat (IRC) and Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Operating, building, or using a botnet to access or control devices without their owners’ authorization is illegal in most jurisdictions and is regularly prosecuted as hacking, fraud, or related cyber-crime.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Law enforcement and private parties also use legal tools to disrupt botnets, but those takedowns raise separate legal and constitutional issues.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Botnets are increasingly rented out by cyber criminals as commodities for a variety of purposes, including as booter/stresser services.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Botnet architecture has evolved over time in an effort to evade detection and disruption.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Traditionally, bot programs are constructed as clients which communicate via existing servers.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This allows the **bot herder** (the controller of the botnet) to perform all control from a remote location, which obfuscates the traffic.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Many recent botnets now rely on existing peer-to-peer networks to communicate.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] These P2P bot programs perform the same actions as the client–server model, but they do not require a central server to communicate.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The first botnets on the Internet used a client–server model to accomplish their tasks.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Typically, these botnets operate through Internet Relay Chat networks, domains, or websites.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Infected clients access a predetermined location and await incoming commands from the server.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The bot herder sends commands to the server, which relays them to the clients.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Clients execute the commands and report their results back to the bot herder.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] In the case of IRC botnets, infected clients connect to an infected IRC server and join a channel pre-designated for C&C by the bot herder.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The bot herder sends commands to the channel via the IRC server.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Each client retrieves the commands and executes them.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Clients send messages back to the IRC channel with the results of their actions.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] In response to efforts to detect and decapitate IRC botnets, bot herders have begun deploying malware on peer-to-peer networks.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] These bots may use digital signatures so that only someone with access to the private key can control the botnet, such as in Gameover ZeuS and the ZeroAccess botnet.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Newer botnets fully operate over P2P networks.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Rather than communicate with a centralized server, P2P bots perform as both a command distribution server and a client that receives commands.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This avoids having any single point of failure, which is an issue for centralized botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] In order to find other infected machines, P2P bots discreetly probe random IP addresses until they identify another infected machine.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The contacted bot replies with information such as its software version and list of known bots.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] If one of the bots' version is lower than the other, they will initiate a file transfer to update.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This way, each bot grows its list of infected machines and updates itself by periodically communicating to all known bots.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A botnet's originator (known as a "bot herder" or "bot master") controls the botnet remotely.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This is known as the command-and-control (C&C).
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The program for the operation must communicate via a covert channel to the client on the victim's machine (zombie computer).
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] IRC is a historically favored means of C&C because of its communication protocol.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A bot herder creates an IRC channel for infected clients to join.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Messages sent to the channel are broadcast to all channel members.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The bot herder may set the channel's topic to command the botnet.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] For example, the message `:herder!herder@example.com TOPIC #channel DDoS www.victim.com` from the bot herder alerts all infected clients belonging to #channel to begin a DDoS attack on the website www.victim.com.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] An example response `:bot1!bot1@compromised.net PRIVMSG #channel I am DDoSing www.victim.com` by a bot client alerts the bot herder that it has begun the attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Some botnets implement custom versions of well-known protocols.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The implementation differences can be used for detection of botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] For example, Mega-D features a slightly modified Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) implementation for testing spam capability.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Bringing down the Mega-D's SMTP server disables the entire pool of bots that rely upon the same SMTP server.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] In computer science, a zombie computer is a computer connected to the Internet that has been compromised by a hacker, computer virus or trojan horse and can be used to perform malicious tasks under remote direction.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Botnets of zombie computers are often used to spread e-mail spam and launch denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Most owners of zombie computers are unaware that their system is being used in this way.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Because the owner tends to be unaware, these computers are metaphorically compared to zombies.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A coordinated DDoS attack by multiple botnet machines also resembles a zombie horde attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The process of stealing computing resources as a result of a system being joined to a "botnet" is sometimes referred to as "scrumping".
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Botnet command and control (C&C) protocols have been implemented in a number of ways, from traditional IRC approaches to more sophisticated versions.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Telnet botnets use a simple C&C botnet protocol in which bots connect to the main command server to host the botnet.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Bots are added to the botnet by using a scanning script, which runs on an external server and scans IP ranges for telnet and SSH server default logins.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Once a login is found, the scanning server can infect it through SSH with malware, which pings the control server.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] IRC networks use simple, low-bandwidth communication methods, making them widely used to host botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] They tend to be relatively simple in construction and have been used with moderate success for coordinating DDoS attacks and spam campaigns while being able to continually switch channels to avoid being taken down.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] However, in some cases, merely blocking certain keywords has proven effective in stopping IRC-based botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The RFC 1459 (IRC) standard is popular with botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The first known popular botnet controller script, "MaXiTE Bot" used the IRC XDCC protocol for private control commands.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] One problem with using IRC is that each bot client must know the IRC server, port, and channel to be of any use to the botnet.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Anti-malware organizations can detect and shut down these servers and channels, effectively halting the botnet attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] If this happens, clients are still infected, but they typically lie dormant since they have no way of receiving instructions.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] To mitigate this problem, a botnet can consist of several servers or channels.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] If one of the servers or channels becomes disabled, the botnet simply switches to another.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] It is still possible to detect and disrupt additional botnet servers or channels by sniffing IRC traffic.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A botnet adversary can even potentially gain knowledge of the control scheme and imitate the bot herder by issuing commands correctly.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Since most botnets using IRC networks and domains can be taken down over time, hackers have moved to P2P botnets with C&C to make the botnet more resilient and resistant to termination.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Some have also used encryption as a way to secure or lock down the botnet from others; most of the time when they use encryption it is public-key cryptography and has presented challenges in both implementing it and breaking it.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Many large botnets tend to use domains rather than IRC in their construction (see Rustock botnet and Srizbi botnet).
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] They are usually hosted with bulletproof hosting services.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This is one of the earliest types of C&C.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A zombie computer accesses a specially designed webpage or domain(s) which serves the list of controlling commands.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The advantages of using web pages or domains as C&C is that a large botnet can be effectively controlled and maintained with very simple code that can be readily updated.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Disadvantages of using this method are that it uses a considerable amount of bandwidth at large scale, and domains can be quickly seized by government agencies with little effort.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] If the domains controlling the botnets are not seized, they are also easy targets to compromise with denial-of-service attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Fast-flux DNS can be used to make it difficult to track down the control servers, which may change from day to day.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Control servers may also hop from DNS domain to DNS domain, with domain generation algorithms being used to create new DNS names for controller servers.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Some botnets use free DNS hosting services such as DynDns.org, No-IP.com, and Afraid.org to point a subdomain towards an IRC server that harbors the bots.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] While these free DNS services do not themselves host attacks, they provide reference points (often hard-coded into the botnet executable).
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Removing such services can cripple an entire botnet.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Calling back to popular sites such as GitHub, Twitter, Reddit, Instagram, the XMPP open source instant message protocol and Tor hidden services are popular ways of avoiding egress filtering to communicate with a C&C server.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This example illustrates how a botnet is created and used for malicious gain.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The *bot* instructs the infected PC to connect to a particular command-and-control (C&C) server.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The botmaster may then use the bots to gather keystrokes or use form grabbing to steal online credentials and may rent out the botnet as DDoS and/or spam as a service or sell the credentials online for a profit.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Depending on the quality and capability of the bots, the value is increased or decreased.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Newer bots can automatically scan their environment and propagate themselves using vulnerabilities and weak passwords.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Generally, the more vulnerabilities a bot can scan and propagate through, the more valuable it becomes to a botnet controller community.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Computers can be co-opted into a botnet when they execute malicious software.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This can be accomplished by luring users into making a drive-by download, exploiting web browser vulnerabilities, or by tricking the user into running a Trojan horse program, which may come from an email attachment.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This malware will typically install modules that allow the computer to be commanded and controlled by the botnet's operator.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] After the software is downloaded, it will call home (send a reconnection packet) to the host computer.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] When the reconnection is made, depending on how it is written, a Trojan may then delete itself or may remain present to update and maintain the modules.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] In some cases, a botnet may be temporarily created by volunteer hacktivists, such as with implementations of the Low Orbit Ion Cannon as used by 4chan members during Project Chanology in 2010.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] China's Great Cannon of China allows the modification of legitimate web browsing traffic at internet backbones into China to create a large ephemeral botnet to attack large targets such as GitHub in 2015.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Beginning in July 2009, similar botnet capabilities have also emerged for the growing smartphone market.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Examples include the July 2009 in the "wild" release of the Sexy Space text message worm, the world's first botnet capable SMS worm, which targeted the Symbian operating system in Nokia smartphones.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Later that month, researcher Charlie Miller revealed a proof of concept text message worm for the iPhone at Black Hat Briefings.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Also in July, United Arab Emirates consumers were targeted by the Etisalat BlackBerry spyware program.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] In the 2010s, the security community is divided as to the real-world potential of mobile botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The botnet controller community constantly competes over who has the most bots, the highest overall bandwidth, and the most "high-quality" infected machines, like university, corporate, and even governmental machines.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] While botnets are often named after the malware that created them, multiple botnets typically use the same malware but are operated by different entities.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Botnets can be used for many electronic scams.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] These botnets can be used to distribute malware such as viruses to take control of a regular user's computer/software.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] By taking control of someone's personal computer they have unlimited access to their personal information, including passwords and login information to accounts.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Phishing is the acquiring of login information to the "victim's" accounts with a link the "victim" clicks on that is sent through an email or text.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] A survey by Verizon found that around two-thirds of electronic "espionage" cases come from phishing.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The geographic dispersal of botnets means that each recruit must be individually identified/corralled/repaired and limits the benefits of filtering.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Norton AntiBot was aimed at consumers, but most target enterprises and/or ISPs.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Host-based techniques use heuristics to identify bot behavior that has bypassed conventional anti-virus software.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Network-based approaches tend to use the techniques described above; shutting down C&C servers, null-routing DNS entries, or completely shutting down IRC servers.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] BotHunter is software, developed with support from the U.S.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Army Research Office, that detects botnet activity within a network by analyzing network traffic and comparing it to patterns characteristic of malicious processes.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Detecting automated bot becomes more difficult as newer and more sophisticated generations of bots get launched by attackers.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] For example, an automated attack can deploy a large bot army and apply brute-force methods with highly accurate username and password lists to hack into accounts.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The idea is to overwhelm sites with tens of thousands of requests from different IPs all over the world, but with each bot only submitting a single request every 10 minutes or so, which can result in more than 5 million attempts per day.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] In these cases, many tools try to leverage volumetric detection, but automated bot attacks now have ways of circumventing triggers of volumetric detection.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] One of the techniques for detecting these bot attacks is what's known as "signature-based systems" in which the software will attempt to detect patterns in the request packet.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] However, attacks are constantly evolving, so this may not be a viable option when patterns cannot be discerned from thousands of requests.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] There is also the behavioral approach to thwarting bots, which ultimately tries to distinguish bots from humans.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] By identifying non-human behavior and recognizing known bot behavior, this process can be applied at the user, browser, and network levels.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The most capable method of using software to combat a virus has been to utilize honeypot software in order to convince the malware that a system is vulnerable.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The malicious files are then analyzed using forensic software.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] On 15 July 2014, the Subcommittee on Crime and Terrorism of the Committee on the Judiciary, United States Senate, held a hearing on the threats posed by botnets and the public and private efforts to disrupt and dismantle them.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The rise in vulnerable IoT devices has led to an increase in IoT-based botnet attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] To address this, a novel network-based anomaly detection method for IoT called N-BaIoT was introduced.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] It captures network behavior snapshots and employs deep autoencoders to identify abnormal traffic from compromised IoT devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The method was tested by infecting nine IoT devices with Mirai and BASHLITE botnets, showing its ability to accurately and promptly detect attacks originating from compromised IoT devices within a botnet.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Additionally, comparing different ways of detecting botnets is really useful for researchers.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] It helps them see how well each method works compared to others.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] This kind of comparison is good because it lets researchers evaluate the methods fairly and find ways to make them better.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The first botnet was first acknowledged and exposed by EarthLink during a lawsuit with notorious spammer Khan C.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The botnet was constructed for the purpose of bulk spam, and accounted for nearly 25% of all spam at the time.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] Around 2006, to thwart detection, some botnets were scaling back in size.
[src:iot-security-deep/botnet] The following is a non-exhaustive list of some historical botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The growing significance of computer security reflects the increasing dependence on computer systems, the Internet, and evolving wireless network standards.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] This reliance has expanded with the proliferation of smart devices, including smartphones, televisions, and other components of the Internet of things (IoT).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] As digital infrastructure becomes more embedded in everyday life, cybersecurity has emerged as a critical concern.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The complexity of modern information systems—and the societal functions they underpin—has introduced new vulnerabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Systems that manage essential services, such as power grids, electoral processes, and finance, are particularly sensitive to security breaches.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Although many aspects of computer security involve digital security, such as electronic passwords and encryption, physical security measures, such as metal locks, are still used to prevent unauthorized tampering.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] IT security is not a perfect subset of information security and therefore does not completely align with the security convergence schema.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A vulnerability refers to a flaw in the structure, execution, functioning, or internal oversight of a computer or system that compromises its security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Most of the vulnerabilities that have been discovered are documented in the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) database.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] An *exploitable* vulnerability is one for which at least one working *exploit* exists.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Actors maliciously seeking vulnerabilities are known as *threats*.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Vulnerabilities can be researched, reverse-engineered, hunted, or exploited using automated tools or customized scripts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Various people or parties are vulnerable to cyberattacks; however, different groups are likely to experience different types of attacks more than others.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In April 2023, the United Kingdom Department for Science, Innovation & Technology released a report on cyberattacks over the previous 12 months.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] They surveyed 2,263 UK businesses, 1,174 UK registered charities, and 554 education institutions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Normal internet users are most likely to be affected by untargeted cyberattacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] These are where attackers indiscriminately target as many devices, services, or users as possible.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] They do this using techniques that take advantage of the openness of the Internet.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] These strategies mostly include phishing, ransomware, water holing and scanning.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A backdoor in a computer system, a cryptosystem or an algorithm, is any secret method of bypassing normal authentication or security controls.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] These weaknesses may exist for many reasons, including original design or poor configuration.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Due to the nature of backdoors, they are of greater concern to companies and databases as opposed to individuals.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Backdoors may be added by an authorized party to allow some legitimate access or by an attacker for malicious reasons.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Criminals often use malware to install backdoors, giving them remote administrative access to a system.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Backdoors can be difficult to detect, as they often remain hidden within source code or system firmware and may require intimate knowledge of the operating system to identify.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Denial-of-service attacks (DoS) are designed to make a machine or network resource unavailable to its intended users.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Attackers can deny service to individual victims, such as by deliberately entering an incorrect password enough consecutive times to cause the victim's account to be locked, or they may overload the capabilities of a machine or network and block all users at once.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] While a network attack from a single IP address can be blocked by adding a new firewall rule, many forms of distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attacks are possible, where the attack comes from a large number of points.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In this case, defending against these attacks is much more difficult.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Such attacks can originate from the zombie computers of a botnet or from a range of other possible techniques, including distributed reflective denial-of-service (DRDoS), where innocent systems are fooled into sending traffic to the victim.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] With such attacks, the amplification factor makes the attack easier for the attacker because they have to use little bandwidth themselves.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] To understand why attackers may carry out these attacks, see the 'attacker motivation' section.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A direct-access attack is when an unauthorized user (an attacker) gains physical access to a computer, typically to copy data from it or steal information.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Attackers may also compromise security by making operating system modifications, installing software worms, keyloggers, covert listening devices or using wireless microphones.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Even when the system is protected by standard security measures, these may be bypassed by booting another operating system or tool from a CD-ROM or other bootable media.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Disk encryption and the Trusted Platform Module standard are designed to prevent these attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Direct service attackers are related in concept to direct memory attacks which allow an attacker to gain direct access to a computer's memory.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Eavesdropping is the act of surreptitiously listening to a private computer conversation (communication), usually between hosts on a network.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It typically occurs when a user connects to a network where traffic is not secured or encrypted and sends sensitive business data to a colleague, which, when listened to by an attacker, could be exploited.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Data transmitted across an open network can be intercepted by an attacker using various methods.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Unlike malware, direct-access attacks, or other forms of cyberattacks, eavesdropping attacks are unlikely to negatively affect the performance of networks or devices, making them difficult to notice.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In fact, "the attacker does not need to have any ongoing connection to the software at all.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Using a virtual private network (VPN), which encrypts data between two points, is one of the most common forms of protection against eavesdropping.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Using the best form of encryption possible for wireless networks is best practice, as well as using HTTPS instead of an unencrypted HTTP.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Programs such as Carnivore and NarusInSight have been used by the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) and the NSA to eavesdrop on the systems of internet service providers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Even machines that operate as a closed system (i.e., with no contact with the outside world) can be eavesdropped upon by monitoring the faint electromagnetic transmissions generated by the hardware.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] TEMPEST is a specification by the NSA referring to these attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Man-in-the-middle attacks (MITM) involve a malicious attacker trying to intercept, surveil or modify communications between two parties by spoofing one or both party's identities and injecting themselves in-between.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Surfacing in 2017, a new class of multi-vector, polymorphic cyber threats combine several types of attacks and change form to avoid cybersecurity controls as they spread.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Multi-vector polymorphic attacks, as the name describes, are both multi-vectored and polymorphic.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Firstly, they are a singular attack that involves multiple methods of attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In this sense, they are "multi-vectored" (i.e. the attack can use multiple means of propagation such as via the Web, email and applications).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Phishing is the attempt to acquire sensitive information such as usernames, passwords, and credit card details directly from users by deceiving the users.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Phishing is typically carried out by email spoofing, instant messaging, text message, or on a phone call.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] They often direct users to enter details at a fake website whose look and feel are almost identical to the legitimate one.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The fake website often asks for personal information, such as login details and passwords.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] This information can then be used to gain access to the individual's real account on the real website.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Preying on a victim's trust, phishing can be classified as a form of social engineering.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Attackers can use creative ways to gain access to real accounts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A common scam is for attackers to send fake electronic invoices to individuals showing that they recently purchased music, apps, or others, and instructing them to click on a link if the purchases were not authorized.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A more strategic type of phishing is spear-phishing which leverages personal or organization-specific details to make the attacker appear like a trusted source.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Spear-phishing attacks target specific individuals, rather than the broad net cast by phishing attempts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Privilege escalation describes a situation where an attacker with limited access is able, without authorization, to elevate their privileges or access level.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] For example, a standard computer user may be able to exploit a vulnerability in the system to gain access to restricted data; or even become *root* and have full unrestricted access to a system.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The severity of attacks can range from attacks simply sending an unsolicited email to a ransomware attack on large amounts of data.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Privilege escalation usually starts with social engineering techniques, often phishing.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Any computational system affects its environment in some form.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] This effect it has on its environment can range from electromagnetic radiation, to residual effect on RAM cells which as a consequence make a cold boot attack possible, to hardware implementation faults that allow for access or guessing of other values that normally should be inaccessible.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In Side-channel attack scenarios, the attacker would gather such information about a system or network to guess its internal state and as a result access the information which is assumed by the victim to be secure.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The target information in a side channel can be challenging to detect due to its low amplitude when combined with other signals.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Social engineering, in the context of computer security, aims to convince a user to disclose secrets such as passwords, card numbers, etc. or grant physical access by, for example, impersonating a senior executive, bank, a contractor, or a customer.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] This generally involves exploiting people's trust, and relying on their cognitive biases.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A common scam involves emails sent to accounting and finance department personnel, impersonating their CEO and urgently requesting action.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] One of the main techniques of social engineering are phishing attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In early 2016, the FBI reported that such business email compromise (BEC) scams had cost US businesses more than $2 billion in about two years.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In May 2016, the Milwaukee Bucks NBA team was the victim of this type of cyber scam with a perpetrator impersonating the team's president Peter Feigin, resulting in the handover of all the team's employees' 2015 W-2 tax forms.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Spoofing is an act of pretending to be a valid entity through the falsification of data (such as an IP address or username), in order to gain access to information or resources that one is otherwise unauthorized to obtain.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Spoofing is closely related to phishing.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In 2018, the cybersecurity firm Trellix published research on the life-threatening risk of spoofing in the healthcare industry.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Tampering describes a malicious modification or alteration of data.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It is an intentional but unauthorized act resulting in the modification of a system, components of systems, its intended behavior, or data.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] So-called Evil Maid attacks and security services planting of surveillance capability into routers are examples.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] HTML smuggling allows an attacker to *smuggle* a malicious code inside a particular HTML or web page.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] HTML files can carry payloads concealed as benign, inert data in order to defeat content filters.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] These payloads can be reconstructed on the other side of the filter.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] When a target user opens the HTML, the malicious code is activated; the web browser then *decodes* the script, which then unleashes the malware onto the target's device.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Information security (InfoSec) and cybersecurity are closely related but not identical.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] While cybersecurity addresses external and malicious threats related to the exposure to the internet, information security also covers internal policies, roles, and controls.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Employee behavior can have a big impact on information security in organizations.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Cultural concepts can help different segments of the organization work effectively or work against effectiveness toward information security within an organization.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Andersson and Reimers (2014) found that employees often do not see themselves as part of their organization's information security effort and often take actions that impede organizational changes.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Indeed, the Verizon Data Breach Investigations Report 2020, which examined 3,950 security breaches, discovered 30% of cybersecurity incidents involved internal actors within a company.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Research shows information security culture needs to be improved continuously.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In computer security, a countermeasure is an action, device, procedure or technique that reduces a threat, a vulnerability, or an attack by eliminating or preventing it, by minimizing the harm it can cause, or by discovering and reporting it so that corrective action can be taken.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Security by design, or alternately secure by design, means that the software has been designed from the ground up to be secure.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In this case, security is considered a main feature.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Companies should design and centre their security around techniques and defences which make attacking their data or systems inherently more challenging for attackers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Companies should ensure that their core services that rely on technology are protected so that the systems are essentially never down.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Although systems can be created which are safe against a multitude of attacks, that does not mean that attacks will not be attempted.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Despite one's security, all companies' systems should aim to be able to detect and spot attacks as soon as they occur to ensure the most effective response to them.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Companies should create secure systems designed so that any attack that is successful has minimal severity.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Similarly, Techopedia defines security architecture as "a unified security design that addresses the necessities and potential risks involved in a certain scenario or environment.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It also specifies when and where to apply security controls.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Practicing security architecture provides the right foundation to systematically address business, IT and security concerns in an organization.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A state of computer security is the conceptual ideal, attained by the use of three processes: threat prevention, detection, and response.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Today, computer security consists mainly of preventive measures, like firewalls or an exit procedure.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A firewall can be defined as a way of filtering network data between a host or a network and another network, such as the Internet.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] They can be implemented as software running on the machine, hooking into the network stack (or, in the case of most UNIX-based operating systems such as Linux, built into the operating system kernel) to provide real-time filtering and blocking.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Another implementation is a so-called *physical firewall*, which consists of a separate machine filtering network traffic.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Firewalls are common amongst machines that are permanently connected to the Internet.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Some organizations are turning to big data platforms, such as Apache Hadoop, to extend data accessibility and machine learning to detect advanced persistent threats.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In order to ensure adequate security, the confidentiality, integrity and availability of a network, known as the CIA triad, must be protected and is considered the foundation of information security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] To achieve those objectives, administrative, physical and technical security measures should be employed.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The amount of security afforded to an asset can only be determined when its value is known.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Vulnerability management is the cycle of identifying, fixing or mitigating vulnerabilities, especially in software and firmware.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Vulnerability management is integral to computer security and network security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Vulnerabilities can be discovered with a vulnerability scanner, which analyzes a computer system in search of known vulnerabilities, such as open ports, insecure software configuration, and susceptibility to malware.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In order for these tools to be effective, they must be kept up to date with every new update the vendor releases.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Typically, these updates will scan for the new vulnerabilities that were introduced recently.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Beyond vulnerability scanning, many organizations contract outside security auditors to run regular penetration tests against their systems to identify vulnerabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In some sectors, this is a contractual requirement.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The act of assessing and reducing vulnerabilities to cyberattacks is commonly referred to as information technology security assessments.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] They aim to assess systems for risk and to predict and test for their vulnerabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] While formal verification of the correctness of computer systems is possible, it is not yet common.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Operating systems formally verified include seL4, and SYSGO's PikeOS – but these make up a very small percentage of the market.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It is possible to reduce an attacker's chances by keeping systems up to date with security patches and updates and by hiring people with expertise in security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Large companies with significant threats can hire Security Operations Centre (SOC) Analysts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Whilst no measures can completely guarantee the prevention of an attack, these measures can help mitigate the damage of possible attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The effects of data loss/damage can be also reduced by careful backing up and insurance.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Outside of formal assessments, there are various methods of reducing vulnerabilities, including hardening systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Two factor authentication is a method for mitigating unauthorized access to a system or sensitive information.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It requires *something you know:* a password or PIN, and *something you have*: a card, dongle, cellphone, or another piece of hardware.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] This increases security as an unauthorized person needs both of these to gain access.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Protecting against social engineering and direct computer access (physical) attacks can only happen by non-computer means, which can be difficult to enforce, relative to the sensitivity of the information.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Training is often involved to help mitigate this risk by improving people's knowledge of how to protect themselves and by increasing people's awareness of threats.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] However, even in highly disciplined environments (e.g., military organizations), social engineering attacks can still be difficult to foresee and prevent.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Inoculation, derived from inoculation theory, seeks to prevent social engineering and other fraudulent tricks and traps by instilling a resistance to persuasion attempts through exposure to similar or related attempts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Hardware-based or assisted computer security also offers an alternative to software-only computer security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Using devices and methods such as dongles, trusted platform modules, intrusion-aware cases, drive locks, disabling USB ports, and mobile-enabled access may be considered more secure due to the physical access (or sophisticated backdoor access) required in order to be compromised.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Each of these is covered in more detail below.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] One use of the term *computer security* refers to technology that is used to implement secure operating systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Using secure operating systems is a good way of ensuring computer security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] These are systems that have achieved certification from an external security-auditing organization, the most popular evaluations are Common Criteria (CC).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] In software engineering, secure coding aims to guard against the accidental introduction of security vulnerabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It is also possible to create software designed from the ground up to be secure.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Beyond this, formal verification aims to prove the correctness of the algorithms underlying a system; important for cryptographic protocols for example.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Within computer systems, two of the main security models capable of enforcing privilege separation are access control lists (ACLs) and role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] An access-control list (ACL), with respect to a computer file system, is a list of permissions associated with an object.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] An ACL specifies which users or system processes are granted access to objects, as well as what operations are allowed on given objects.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Role-based access control is an approach to restricting system access to authorized users, used by the majority of enterprises with more than 500 employees, and can implement mandatory access control (MAC) or discretionary access control (DAC).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A further approach, capability-based security has been mostly restricted to research operating systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Capabilities can, however, also be implemented at the language level, leading to a style of programming that is essentially a refinement of standard object-oriented design.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] An open-source project in the area is the E language.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The end-user is widely recognized as the weakest link in the security chain and it is estimated that more than 90% of security incidents and breaches involve some kind of human error.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Among the most commonly recorded forms of errors and misjudgment are poor password management, sending emails containing sensitive data and attachments to the wrong recipient, the inability to recognize misleading URLs and to identify fake websites and dangerous email attachments.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] A common mistake that users make is saving their user id/password in their browsers to make it easier to log in to banking sites.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] This is a gift to attackers who have obtained access to a machine by some means.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The risk may be mitigated by the use of two-factor authentication.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Related to end-user training, **digital hygiene** or **cyber hygiene** is a fundamental principle relating to information security and, as the analogy with personal hygiene shows, is the equivalent of establishing simple routine measures to minimize the risks from cyber threats.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The assumption is that good cyber hygiene practices can give networked users another layer of protection, reducing the risk that one vulnerable node will be used to either mount attacks or compromise another node or network, especially from common cyberattacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Cyber hygiene should also not be mistaken for proactive cyber defence, a military term.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] The most common acts of digital hygiene can include updating malware protection, cloud back-ups, passwords, and ensuring restricted admin rights and network firewalls.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] As opposed to a purely technology-based defense against threats, cyber hygiene mostly regards routine measures that are technically simple to implement and mostly dependent on discipline or education.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It can be thought of as an abstract list of tips or measures that have been demonstrated as having a positive effect on personal or collective digital security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] As such, these measures can be performed by laypeople, not just security experts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Cyber hygiene relates to personal hygiene as computer viruses relate to biological viruses (or pathogens).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] However, while the term *computer virus* was coined almost simultaneously with the creation of the first working computer viruses, the term *cyber hygiene* is a much later invention, perhaps as late as 2000 by Internet pioneer Vint Cerf.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] It has since been adopted by the Congress and Senate of the United States, the FBI, EU institutions and heads of state.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p01] Where an attack succeeds and a breach occurs, many jurisdictions now have in place mandatory security breach notification laws.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The growth in the number of computer systems and the increasing reliance upon them by individuals, businesses, industries, and governments means that there are an increasing number of systems at risk.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The computer systems of financial regulators and financial institutions like the U.S.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Securities and Exchange Commission, SWIFT, investment banks, and commercial banks are prominent hacking targets for cybercriminals interested in manipulating markets and making illicit gains.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Websites and apps that accept or store credit card numbers, brokerage accounts, and bank account information are also prominent hacking targets, because of the potential for immediate financial gain from transferring money, making purchases, or selling the information on the black market.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In-store payment systems and ATMs have also been tampered with in order to gather customer account data and PINs.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The UCLA Internet Report: Surveying the Digital Future (2000) found that the privacy of personal data created barriers to online sales and that more than nine out of 10 internet users were somewhat or very concerned about credit card security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Several versions of SSL and TLS are commonly used today in applications such as web browsing, e-mail, internet faxing, instant messaging, and VoIP (voice-over-IP).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] There are various interoperable implementations of these technologies, including at least one implementation that is open source.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Open source allows anyone to view the application's source code, and look for and report vulnerabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The credit card companies Visa and MasterCard cooperated to develop the secure EMV chip which is embedded in credit cards.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Further developments include the Chip Authentication Program where banks give customers hand-held card readers to perform online secure transactions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Other developments in this arena include the development of technology such as Instant Issuance which has enabled shopping mall kiosks acting on behalf of banks to issue on-the-spot credit cards to interested customers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Computers control functions at many utilities, including coordination of telecommunications, the power grid, nuclear power plants, and valve opening and closing in water and gas networks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Internet is a potential attack vector for such machines if connected, but the Stuxnet worm demonstrated that even equipment controlled by computers not connected to the Internet can be vulnerable.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In 2014, the Computer Emergency Readiness Team, a division of the Department of Homeland Security, investigated 79 hacking incidents at energy companies.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The aviation industry is very reliant on a series of complex systems which could be attacked.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A simple power outage at one airport can cause repercussions worldwide, much of the system relies on radio transmissions which could be disrupted, and controlling aircraft over oceans is especially dangerous because radar surveillance only extends 175 to 225 miles offshore.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] There is also potential for attack from within an aircraft.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Implementing fixes in aerospace systems poses a unique challenge because efficient air transportation is heavily affected by weight and volume.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Improving security by adding physical devices to airplanes could increase their unloaded weight, and could potentially reduce cargo or passenger capacity.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In Europe, with the (Pan-European Network Service) and NewPENS, and in the US with the NextGen program, air navigation service providers are moving to create their own dedicated networks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Many modern passports are now biometric passports, containing an embedded microchip that stores a digitized photograph and personal information such as name, gender, and date of birth.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In addition, more countries are introducing facial recognition technology to reduce identity-related fraud.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The introduction of the ePassport has assisted border officials in verifying the identity of the passport holder, thus allowing for quick passenger processing.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Plans are under way in the US, the UK, and Australia to introduce SmartGate kiosks with both retina and fingerprint recognition technology.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The airline industry is moving from the use of traditional paper tickets towards the use of electronic tickets (e-tickets).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] These have been made possible by advances in online credit card transactions in partnership with the airlines.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Long-distance bus companies are also switching over to e-ticketing transactions today.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The consequences of a successful attack range from loss of confidentiality to loss of system integrity, air traffic control outages, loss of aircraft, and even loss of life.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Desktop computers and laptops are commonly targeted to gather passwords or financial account information or to construct a botnet to attack another target.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] WiFi, Bluetooth, and cell phone networks on any of these devices could be used as attack vectors, and sensors might be remotely activated after a successful breach.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The increasing number of home automation devices such as the Nest thermostat are also potential targets.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Today many healthcare providers and health insurance companies use the internet to provide enhanced products and services.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Examples are the use of tele-health to potentially offer better quality and access to healthcare, or fitness trackers to lower insurance premiums.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Patient records are increasingly being placed on secure in-house networks, alleviating the need for extra storage space.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In many cases attacks are aimed at financial gain through identity theft and involve data breaches.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Examples include the loss of millions of clients' credit card and financial details by Home Depot, Staples, Target Corporation, and Equifax.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Medical records have been targeted in general identify theft, health insurance fraud, and impersonating patients to obtain prescription drugs for recreational purposes or resale.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Although cyber threats continue to increase, 62% of all organizations did not increase security training for their business in 2015.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Vehicles are increasingly computerized, with engine timing, cruise control, anti-lock brakes, seat belt tensioners, door locks, airbags and advanced driver-assistance systems on many models.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Additionally, connected cars may use WiFi and Bluetooth to communicate with onboard consumer devices and the cell phone network.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Self-driving cars are expected to be even more complex.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] All of these systems carry some security risks, and such issues have gained wide attention.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Simple examples of risk include a malicious compact disc being used as an attack vector, and the car's onboard microphones being used for eavesdropping.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] However, if access is gained to a car's internal controller area network, the danger is much greater – and in a widely publicized 2015 test, hackers remotely carjacked a vehicle from 10 miles away and drove it into a ditch.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Manufacturers are reacting in numerous ways, with Tesla in 2016 pushing out some security fixes *over the air* into its cars' computer systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In the area of autonomous vehicles, in September 2016 the United States Department of Transportation announced some initial safety standards, and called for states to come up with uniform policies.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Additionally, e-Drivers' licenses are being developed using the same technology.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] For example, Mexico's licensing authority (ICV) has used a smart card platform to issue the first e-Drivers' licenses to the city of Monterrey, in the state of Nuevo León.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Shipping companies have adopted RFID (Radio Frequency Identification) technology as an efficient, digitally secure, tracking device.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Unlike a barcode, RFID can be read up to 20 feet away.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Government and military computer systems are commonly attacked by activists and foreign powers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This includes local and regional government infrastructure such as traffic light controls, police and intelligence agency communications, personnel records, as well as student records.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Internet of things (IoT) is the network of physical objects such as devices, vehicles, and buildings that are embedded with electronics, software, sensors, and network connectivity that enables them to collect and exchange data.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Concerns have been raised that this is being developed without appropriate consideration of the security challenges involved.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] While the IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, it also provides opportunities for misuse.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In particular, as the Internet of Things spreads widely, cyberattacks are likely to become an increasingly physical (rather than simply virtual) threat.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] If a front door's lock is connected to the Internet, and can be locked/unlocked from a phone, then a criminal could enter the home at the press of a button from a stolen or hacked phone.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] People could stand to lose much more than their credit card numbers in a world controlled by IoT-enabled devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Thieves have also used electronic means to circumvent non-Internet-connected hotel door locks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] An attack aimed at physical infrastructure or human lives is often called a cyber-kinetic attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] As IoT devices and appliances become more widespread, the prevalence and potential damage of cyber-kinetic attacks can increase substantially.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Medical devices have either been successfully attacked or had potentially deadly vulnerabilities demonstrated, including both in-hospital diagnostic equipment and implanted devices including pacemakers and insulin pumps.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] There are many reports of hospitals and hospital organizations getting hacked, including ransomware attacks, Windows XP exploits, viruses, and data breaches of sensitive data stored on hospital servers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] On 28 December 2016 the US Food and Drug Administration released its recommendations for how medical device manufacturers should maintain the security of Internet-connected devices – but no structure for enforcement.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In distributed generation systems, the risk of a cyberattack is real, according to *Daily Energy Insider*.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] An attack could cause a loss of power in a large area for a long period of time, and such an attack could have just as severe consequences as a natural disaster.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The District of Columbia is considering creating a Distributed Energy Resources (DER) Authority within the city, with the goal being for customers to have more insight into their own energy use and giving the local electric utility, Pepco, the chance to better estimate energy demand.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Perhaps the most widely known digitally secure telecommunication device is the SIM (Subscriber Identity Module) card, a device that is embedded in most of the world's cellular devices before any service can be obtained.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The SIM card is just the beginning of this digitally secure environment.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Smart Card Web Servers draft standard (SCWS) defines the interfaces to an HTTP server in a smart card.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Tests are being conducted to secure OTA ("over-the-air") payment and credit card information from and to a mobile phone.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Combination SIM/DVD devices are being developed through Smart Video Card technology which embeds a DVD-compliant optical disc into the card body of a regular SIM card.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Other telecommunication developments involving digital security include mobile signatures, which use the embedded SIM card to generate a legally binding electronic signature.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Serious financial damage has been caused by security breaches, but because there is no standard model for estimating the cost of an incident, the only data available is that which is made public by the organizations involved.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] "Several computer security consulting firms produce estimates of total worldwide losses attributable to virus and worm attacks and to hostile digital acts in general.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The 2003 loss estimates by these firms range from $13 billion (worms and viruses only) to $226 billion (for all forms of covert attacks).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] However, reasonable estimates of the financial cost of security breaches can actually help organizations make rational investment decisions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] As with physical security, the motivations for breaches of computer security vary between attackers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Some are thrill-seekers or vandals, some are activists, others are criminals looking for financial gain.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] State-sponsored attackers are now common and well resourced but started with amateurs such as Markus Hess who hacked for the KGB, as recounted by Clifford Stoll in *The Cuckoo's Egg*.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Attackers motivations can vary for all types of attacks from pleasure to political goals.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] For example, hacktivists may target a company or organization that carries out activities they do not agree with.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This would be to create bad publicity for the company by having its website crash.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] High capability hackers, often with larger backing or state sponsorship, may attack based on the demands of their financial backers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] These attacks are more likely to attempt more serious attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] An example of a more serious attack was the 2015 Ukraine power grid hack, which reportedly utilised the spear-phishing, destruction of files, and denial-of-service attacks to carry out the full attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Additionally, recent attacker motivations can be traced back to extremist organizations seeking to gain political advantage or disrupt social agendas.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The growth of the internet, mobile technologies, and inexpensive computing devices have led to a rise in capabilities but also to the risk to environments that are deemed as vital to operations.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] All critical targeted environments are susceptible to compromise and this has led to a series of proactive studies on how to migrate the risk by taking into consideration motivations by these types of actors.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Several stark differences exist between the hacker motivation and that of nation state actors seeking to attack based on an ideological preference.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A key aspect of threat modeling for any system is identifying the motivations behind potential attacks and the individuals or groups likely to carry them out.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The level and detail of security measures will differ based on the specific system being protected.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] For instance, a home personal computer, a bank, and a classified military network each face distinct threats, despite using similar underlying technologies.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Computer security incident management is an organized approach to addressing and managing the aftermath of a computer security incident or compromise with the goal of preventing a breach or thwarting a cyberattack.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] An incident that is not identified and managed at the time of intrusion typically escalates to a more damaging event such as a data breach or system failure.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The intended outcome of a computer security incident response plan is to contain the incident, limit damage and assist recovery to business as usual.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Responding to compromises quickly can mitigate exploited vulnerabilities, restore services and processes and minimize losses.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Incident response planning allows an organization to establish a series of best practices to stop an intrusion before it causes damage.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Typical incident response plans contain a set of written instructions that outline the organization's response to a cyberattack.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Without a documented plan in place, an organization may not successfully detect an intrusion or compromise and stakeholders may not understand their roles, processes and procedures during an escalation, slowing the organization's response and resolution.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Post incident activity: Post mortem analysis of the incident, its root cause and the organization's response with the intent of improving the incident response plan and future response efforts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Some illustrative examples of different types of computer security breaches are given below.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In 1988, 60,000 computers were connected to the Internet, and most were mainframes, minicomputers and professional workstations.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] On 2 November 1988, many started to slow down, because they were running a malicious code that demanded processor time and that spread itself to other computers – the first internet computer worm.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The software was traced back to 23-year-old Cornell University graduate student Robert Tappan Morris who said "he wanted to count how many machines were connected to the Internet".
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In 1994, over a hundred intrusions were made by unidentified crackers into the Rome Laboratory, the US Air Force's main command and research facility.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Using trojan horses, hackers were able to obtain unrestricted access to Rome's networking systems and remove traces of their activities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In early 2007, American apparel and home goods company TJX announced that it was the victim of an unauthorized computer systems intrusion and that the hackers had accessed a system that stored data on credit card, debit card, check, and merchandise return transactions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In 2010, the computer worm known as Stuxnet reportedly ruined almost one-fifth of Iran's nuclear centrifuges.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] It did so by disrupting industrial programmable logic controllers (PLCs) in a targeted attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This is generally believed to have been launched by Israel and the United States to disrupt Iran's nuclear program – although neither has publicly admitted this.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In early 2013, documents provided by Edward Snowden were published by *The Washington Post* and *The Guardian* exposing the massive scale of NSA global surveillance.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] There were also indications that the NSA may have inserted a backdoor in a NIST standard for encryption.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This standard was later withdrawn due to widespread criticism.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The NSA additionally were revealed to have tapped the links between Google's data centers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A Ukrainian hacker known as Rescator broke into Target Corporation computers in 2013, stealing roughly 40 million credit cards, and then Home Depot computers in 2014, stealing between 53 and 56 million credit card numbers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Warnings were delivered at both corporations, but ignored; physical security breaches using self checkout machines are believed to have played a large role.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The size of the thefts has resulted in major attention from state and Federal United States authorities and the investigation is ongoing.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In April 2015, the Office of Personnel Management discovered it had been hacked more than a year earlier in a data breach, resulting in the theft of approximately 21.5 million personnel records handled by the office.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Office of Personnel Management hack has been described by federal officials as among the largest breaches of government data in the history of the United States.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Data targeted in the breach included personally identifiable information such as Social Security numbers, names, dates and places of birth, addresses, and fingerprints of current and former government employees as well as anyone who had undergone a government background check.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] It is believed the hack was perpetrated by Chinese hackers.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In July 2015, a hacker group known as The Impact Team successfully breached the extramarital relationship website Ashley Madison, created by Avid Life Media.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The group claimed that they had taken not only company data but user data as well.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] After the breach, The Impact Team dumped emails from the company's CEO, to prove their point, and threatened to dump customer data unless the website was taken down permanently.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] When Avid Life Media did not take the site offline the group released two more compressed files, one 9.7GB and the second 20GB.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] After the second data dump, Avid Life Media CEO Noel Biderman resigned; but the website remained to function.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In June 2021, the cyberattack took down the largest fuel pipeline in the U.S. and led to shortages across the East Coast.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] International legal issues of cyberattacks are complicated in nature.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Proving attribution for cybercrimes and cyberattacks is also a major problem for all law enforcement agencies.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] "Computer viruses switch from one country to another, from one jurisdiction to another – moving around the world, using the fact that we don't have the capability to globally police operations like this.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] So the Internet is as if someone [had] given free plane tickets to all the online criminals of the world." The use of techniques such as dynamic DNS, fast flux and bullet proof servers add to the difficulty of investigation and enforcement.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The role of the government is to make regulations to force companies and organizations to protect their systems, infrastructure and information from any cyberattacks, but also to protect its own national infrastructure such as the national power-grid.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The government's regulatory role in cyberspace is complicated.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] For some, cyberspace was seen as a virtual space that was to remain free of government intervention, as can be seen in many of today's libertarian blockchain and bitcoin discussions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Many government officials and experts think that the government should do more and that there is a crucial need for improved regulation, mainly due to the failure of the private sector to solve efficiently the cybersecurity problem.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Clarke said during a panel discussion at the RSA Security Conference in San Francisco, he believes that the "industry only responds when you threaten regulation.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] If the industry doesn't respond (to the threat), you have to follow through." On the other hand, executives from the private sector agree that improvements are necessary, but think that government intervention would affect their ability to innovate efficiently.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] McCarthy analyzed this public-private partnership in cybersecurity and reflected on the role of cybersecurity in the broader constitution of political order.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] On 22 May 2020, the UN Security Council held its second ever informal meeting on cybersecurity to focus on cyber challenges to international peace.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] According to UN Secretary-General António Guterres, new technologies are too often used to violate rights.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] On 14 April 2016, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The GDPR, which came into force on 25 May 2018, grants individuals within the European Union (EU) and the European Economic Area (EEA) the right to the protection of personal data.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The regulation requires that any entity that processes personal data incorporate data protection by design and by default.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] It also requires that certain organizations appoint a Data Protection Officer (DPO).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The IT Security Association TeleTrusT exist in Germany since June 1986, which is an international competence network for IT security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] To protect national network and system security, many countries have established strategies and staffing for computer emergency response teams, proactive cyber defence, and cyber threat intelligence.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] National policy actions typically include cybersecurity regulations and information security standards.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Since 2010, Canada has had a cyber security strategy.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This functions as a counterpart document to the National Strategy and Action Plan for Critical Infrastructure.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The strategy has three main pillars: securing government systems, securing vital private cyber systems, and helping Canadians to be secure online.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] There is also a Cyber Incident Management Framework to provide a coordinated response in the event of a cyber incident.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Canadian Cyber Incident Response Centre (CCIRC) is responsible for mitigating and responding to threats to Canada's critical infrastructure and cyber systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] It provides support to mitigate cyber threats, technical support to respond & recover from targeted cyber attacks, and provides online tools for members of Canada's critical infrastructure sectors.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] It posts regular cyber security bulletins & operates an online reporting tool where individuals and organizations can report a cyber incident.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] To inform the general public on how to protect themselves online, Public Safety Canada has partnered with STOP.THINK.CONNECT, a coalition of non-profit, private sector, and government organizations, and launched the Cyber Security Cooperation Program.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] They also run the GetCyberSafe portal for Canadian citizens, and Cyber Security Awareness Month during October.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Public Safety Canada aims to begin an evaluation of Canada's cybersecurity strategy in early 2015.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Australian federal government announced an $18.2 million investment to fortify the cyber security resilience of small and medium enterprises (SMEs) and enhance their capabilities in responding to cyber threats.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This financial backing is an integral component of the 2023-2030 Australian Cyber Security Strategy.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A substantial allocation of $7.2 million is earmarked for the establishment of a voluntary cyber health check program, facilitating businesses in conducting a comprehensive and tailored self-assessment of their cyber security upskill.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This avant-garde health assessment serves as a diagnostic tool, enabling enterprises to ascertain the robustness of Australia's cyber security regulations.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Furthermore, it affords them access to a repository of educational resources and materials, fostering the acquisition of skills necessary for an elevated cyber security posture.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This groundbreaking initiative was jointly disclosed by Minister for Cyber Security Clare O'Neil and Minister for Small Business Julie Collins.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Hong Kong's Protection of Critical Infrastructures (Computer Systems) Bill (the “Bill”) was passed by the Legislative Council on 19 March 2025, with the purpose to “establish legal requirements for organisations designated as critical infrastructure operators”.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Some provisions for cybersecurity have been incorporated into rules framed under the Information Technology Act 2000.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] CERT- In is the nodal agency which monitors the cyber threats in the country.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The post of National Cyber Security Coordinator has also been created in the Prime Minister's Office (PMO).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Indian Companies Act 2013 has also introduced cyber law and cyber security obligations on the part of Indian directors.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Some provisions for cyber security have been incorporated into rules framed under the Information Technology Act 2000 Update in 2013.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Following cyberattacks in the first half of 2013, when the government, news media, television stations, and bank websites were compromised, the national government committed to the training of 5,000 new cybersecurity experts by 2017.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The South Korean government blamed its northern counterpart for these attacks, as well as incidents that occurred in 2009, 2011, and 2012, but Pyongyang denies the accusations.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In 2016 the National Cyber Security Centre was formed as the central body overseeing cybersecurity in the UK, as part of GCHQ.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The UK government published a National Cyber Security Strategy in 2022 assigning £2.6bn for industry, skills and national security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In addition, the National Cyber Force, launched in 2020, works with GCHQ and the Ministry of Defence and aims to "transform the UK's ability to contest adversaries in cyber space, to protect the country, its people and our way of life".
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In 2013, executive order 13636 *Improving Critical Infrastructure Cybersecurity* was signed, which prompted the creation of the NIST Cybersecurity Framework.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The 2018 cyber strategy called for specific measures to harden U.S. government networks from attacks, such as the June 2015 intrusion into the U.S.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Office of Personnel Management (OPM), which compromised the records of about 4.2 million current and former government employees.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Biden administration released a comprehensive National Cybersecurity Strategy in 2023.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act prohibits unauthorized access or damage of protected computers as defined in 18 U.S.C. § 1030(e)(2).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The General Services Administration (GSA) has standardized the *penetration test* service as a pre-vetted support service, to rapidly address potential vulnerabilities, and stop adversaries before they impact US federal, state and local governments.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] These services are commonly referred to as Highly Adaptive Cybersecurity Services (HACS).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Department of Homeland Security has a dedicated division responsible for the response system, risk management program and requirements for cyber security in the United States called the National Cyber Security Division.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The division is home to US-CERT operations and the National Cyber Alert System.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The National Cybersecurity and Communications Integration Center brings together government organizations responsible for protecting computer networks and networked infrastructure.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In addition to its own specific duties, the FBI participates alongside non-profit organizations such as InfraGard.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section (CCIPS) operates in the United States Department of Justice Criminal Division.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The CCIPS is in charge of investigating computer crime and intellectual property crime and is specialized in the search and seizure of digital evidence in computers and networks.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Food and Drug Administration has issued guidance for medical devices, and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration is concerned with automotive cyber security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Concerns have also been raised about the future Next Generation Air Transportation System.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Andersson and Reimers (2019) report these certifications range from CompTIA's A+ and Security+ through the ICS2.org's CISSP, etc.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In the context of U.S. nuclear power plants, the U.S.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) outlines cyber security requirements under 10 CFR Part 73, specifically in 10 CFR 73.54.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The Nuclear Energy Institute's NEI 08-09 document, *Cyber Security Plan for Nuclear Power Reactors*, outlines a comprehensive framework for cybersecurity in the nuclear power industry.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] There is growing concern that cyberspace will become the next theater of warfare.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] This has led to new terms such as *cyberwarfare* and *cyberterrorism*.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The United States Cyber Command was created in 2009 and many other countries have similar forces.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] There are a few critics that question whether cyber security is as significant a threat as it is made out to be.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Cyber security is a fast-growing field of IT concerned with reducing organizations' risk of getting hacked or data breaches.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] According to research from the Enterprise Strategy Group, 46% of organizations say that they have a "problematic shortage" of cyber security skills in 2016, up from 28% in 2015.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Commercial, government and non-governmental organizations all employ cybersecurity professionals.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The fastest increases in demand for cyber security workers are in industries managing increasing volumes of consumer data such as finance, health care, and retail.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] However, the use of the term *cybersecurity* is more prevalent in government job descriptions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Analyzes and assesses vulnerabilities in the infrastructure (software, hardware, networks), investigates using available tools and countermeasures to remedy the detected vulnerabilities and recommends solutions and best practices.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Analyzes and assesses damage to the data/infrastructure as a result of security incidents, examines available recovery tools and processes, and recommends solutions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Tests for compliance with security policies and procedures.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] May assist in the creation, implementation, or management of security solutions.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Performs security monitoring, security and data/logs analysis, and forensic analysis, to detect security incidents, and mount the incident response.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Investigates and utilizes new technologies and processes to enhance security capabilities and implement improvements.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Designs a security system or major components of a security system, and may head a security design team building a new security system.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A high-level management position responsible for the entire information security division/staff.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The position may include hands-on technical work.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A high-level management position responsible for the entire security division/staff.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A newer position is now deemed needed as security risks grow.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] ), data protection policies, awareness-raising, training, and audits.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Student programs are also available for people interested in beginning a career in cyber security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] Meanwhile, an alternative option for information security professionals of varied experience levels to keep studying is online security training, including webcasts.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] A wide range of courses are also available.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In the United Kingdom, a nationwide set of cyber security forums, known as the U.K Cyber Security Forum, were established supported by the Government's cyber security strategy in order to encourage start-ups and innovation and to address the skills gap identified by the U.K Government.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] In Singapore, the Cyber Security Agency has issued a Singapore Operational Technology (OT) Cybersecurity Competency Framework (OTCCF).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The framework defines emerging cybersecurity roles in Operational Technology.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] The OTCCF was endorsed by the Infocomm Media Development Authority (IMDA).
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] It outlines the different OT cybersecurity job positions as well as the technical skills and core competencies necessary.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p02] It also depicts the many career paths available, including vertical and lateral advancement opportunities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Since the Internet's arrival and with the digital transformation initiated in recent years, the notion of cybersecurity has become a familiar subject in both our professional and personal lives.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Cybersecurity and cyber threats have been consistently present for the last 60 years of technological change.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] In the 1970s and 1980s, computer security was mainly limited to academia until the conception of the Internet, where, with increased connectivity, computer viruses and network intrusions began to take off.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] After the spread of viruses in the 1990s, the 2000s marked the institutionalization of organized attacks such as distributed denial of service.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] This led to the formalization of cybersecurity as a professional discipline.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] The April 1967 session organized by Willis Ware at the Spring Joint Computer Conference, and the later publication of the Ware Report, were foundational moments in the history of the field of computer security.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Ware's work straddled the intersection of material, cultural, political, and social concerns.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] A 1977 NIST publication introduced the *CIA triad* of confidentiality, integrity, and availability as a clear and simple way to describe key security goals.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] While still relevant, many more elaborate frameworks have since been proposed.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] However, in the 1970s and 1980s, there were no grave computer threats because computers and the internet were still in the early stages of development, and security threats were easily identifiable.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] More often, threats came from malicious insiders who gained unauthorized access to sensitive documents and files.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Although malware and network breaches existed during the early years, they did not use them for financial gain.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] By the second half of the 1970s, established computer firms like IBM started offering commercial access control systems and computer security software products.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] One of the earliest examples of an attack on a computer network was the computer worm Creeper written by Bob Thomas at BBN, which propagated through the ARPANET in 1971.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] The program was purely experimental in nature and carried no malicious payload.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] A later program, Reaper, was created by Ray Tomlinson in 1972 and used to destroy Creeper.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Between September 1986 and June 1987, a group of German hackers performed the first documented case of cyber espionage.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] The group hacked into American defense contractors, universities, and military base networks and sold gathered information to the Soviet KGB.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] The group was led by Markus Hess, who was arrested on 29 June 1987.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] He was convicted of espionage (along with two co-conspirators) on 15 Feb 1990.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] In 1988, one of the first computer worms, called the Morris worm, was distributed via the Internet.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] It gained significant mainstream media attention.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Netscape started developing the protocol SSL, shortly after the National Center for Supercomputing Applications (NCSA) launched Mosaic 1.0, the first web browser, in 1993.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Netscape had SSL version 1.0 ready in 1994, but it was never released to the public due to many serious security vulnerabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] However, in 1995, Netscape launched Version 2.0.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] The National Security Agency (NSA) is responsible for the protection of U.S. information systems and also for collecting foreign intelligence.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] The agency analyzes commonly used software and system configurations to find security flaws, which it can use for offensive purposes against competitors of the United States.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] NSA contractors created and sold *click-and-shoot* attack tools to US agencies and close allies, but eventually, the tools made their way to foreign adversaries.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] In 2016, NSAs own hacking tools were hacked, and Russia and North Korea have used it.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] NSA's employees and contractors have been recruited at high salaries by adversaries, anxious to compete in cyberwarfare.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] In 2007, the United States and Israel began exploiting security flaws in the Microsoft Windows operating system to attack and damage equipment used in Iran to refine nuclear materials.
[src:iot-security-deep/computer-security-p03] Iran responded by heavily investing in their own cyberwarfare capability, which it began using against the United States.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:iot-security-deep/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:iot-security-deep/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The software was initially used by the creators to DDoS *Minecraft* servers and companies offering DDoS protection to *Minecraft* servers, with the authors using Mirai to operate a protection racket.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The source code for Mirai was subsequently published on Hack Forums as open-source.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Since the source code was published, the techniques have been adapted in other malware projects.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Devices infected by Mirai continuously scan the internet for the IP address of Internet of things (IoT) devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Mirai includes a table of IP address ranges that it will not infect, including private networks and addresses allocated to the United States Postal Service and Department of Defense.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Mirai then identifies vulnerable IoT devices using a table of more than 60 common factory default usernames and passwords, and logs into them to infect them.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Infected devices will continue to function normally, except for occasional sluggishness, and an increased use of bandwidth.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] A device remains infected until it is rebooted, which may involve simply turning the device off and after a short wait turning it back on.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] After a reboot, unless the login password is changed immediately, the device will be reinfected within minutes.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Upon infection Mirai will identify any "competing" malware, remove it from memory, and block remote administration ports.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Victim IoT devices are identified by “first entering a rapid scanning phase where it asynchronously and “statelessly” sent TCP SYN probes to pseudo-random IPv4 addresses, excluding those in a hard-coded IP blacklist, on telnet TCP ports 23 and 2323”.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] If an IoT device responds to the probe, the attack then enters into a brute-force login phase.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] During this phase, the attacker tries to establish a telnet connection using predetermined username and password pairs from a list of credentials.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Most of these logins are default usernames and passwords from the IoT vendor.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] If the IoT device allows the Telnet access, the victim's IP, along with the successfully used credential is sent to a collection server.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] There are a large number of IoT devices which use default settings, making them vulnerable to infection.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Once infected, the device will monitor a command and control server which indicates the target of an attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The reason for the use of the large number of IoT devices is to bypass some anti-DoS software which monitors the IP address of incoming requests and filters or sets up a block if it identifies an abnormal traffic pattern, for example, if too many requests come from a particular IP address.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Other reasons include to be able to marshall more bandwidth than the perpetrator can assemble alone, and to avoid being traced.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Mirai as an Internet of things (IoT) devices threat has not been stopped after the arrest of the actors due to the fact that other actors have utilized the source code on GitHub to evolve Mirai into new *variants* .
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Some speculate that the goal is to expand its botnet node to many more IoT devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The detail of the recent progress of these variants is listed in the following paragraphs.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On 12 December 2017, researchers identified a *variant* of Mirai exploiting a zero-day flaw in *Huawei HG532 routers* to accelerate Mirai botnets infection, implementing two known SOAP related exploits on routers web interface, CVE-2014–8361 and CVE-2017–17215.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On 14 January 2018, a new variant of Mirai dubbed “Okiru”, the Japanese word for "get up," already targeting popular embedded processor like ARM, MIPS, x86, PowerPC and others was found targeting ARC processors based Linux devices for the first time.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Only a relatively small number of ARC-based devices run Linux and are therefore exposed to Mirai.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On 18 January 2018, a successor of Mirai is reported to be designed to hijack cryptocurrency mining operations.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On 26 January 2018, two similar Mirai variant botnets were reported, the more modified version of which weaponizes EDB 38722 D-Link router's exploit to enlist further vulnerable IoT devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The vulnerability in the router's Home Network Administration Protocol (HNAP) is utilized to craft a malicious query to exploited routers that can bypass authentication, to then cause an arbitrary remote code execution.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The less modified version of Mirai is called "Masuta" (after the Japanese transliteration of "Master"), while the more modified version is called "PureMasuta".
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] In March 2018, a new variant of Mirai, dubbed as "OMG", has emerged to surface with added configurations to target vulnerable IoT devices and turning them into proxy servers.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] New firewall rules that allow traffic to travel through the generated HTTP and SOCKS ports were added configurations to the Mirai code.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Once these ports are open to traffic, OMG sets up 3proxy – open-source software available on a Russian website.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Between May and June 2018, another variant of Mirai, dubbed as "Wicked", has emerged with added configurations to target at least three additional exploits including those affecting Netgear routers and CCTV-DVRs.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Wicked scans ports 8080, 8443, 80, and 81 and attempts to locate vulnerable, unpatched IoT devices running on those ports.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Researchers suspect the same author created the Wicked, Sora, Owari, and Omni botnets.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] In the same month it was published a report of infection campaign of Mirai malware to Android devices through the Android Debug Bridge on TCP/5555, an optional feature in the Android operating system, though it was discovered that this feature appears to be enabled on some Android phones.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] At the end of 2018, a Mirai variant dubbed "Miori" started being spread through a remote code execution vulnerability in the ThinkPHP framework, affecting versions 5.0.23 to 5.1.31.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] This vulnerability is continuously being abused by the further evolved Mirai variants dubbed as "Hakai" and "Yowai" in January 2019, and variant "SpeakUp" in February, 2019.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The Mirai-based “Gayfemboy” botnet, discovered in 2024, targets global systems and exploits multiple vulnerabilities.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The recent Mirai based "Aisuru" botnet, first discovered by XLab in August 2024, believed to have over 300,000 compromised devices, has been causing record breaking DDoS attacks ever since, As of February 2026, has been responsible for the 31.4 Tbps on Cloudflare.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Mirai was used, alongside BASHLITE, in the DDoS attack on 20 September 2016 on the Krebs on Security site which reached 620 Gbit/s.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Ars Technica also reported a 1 Tbit/s attack on French web host OVH.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On 21 October 2016, multiple major DDoS attacks in DNS services of DNS service provider Dyn occurred using Mirai malware installed on a large number of IoT devices, many of which were still using their default usernames and passwords.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] These attacks resulted in the inaccessibility of several high-profile websites, including GitHub, Twitter, Reddit, Netflix, Airbnb and many others.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The attribution of the Dyn attack to the Mirai botnet was originally reported by Level 3 Communications.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Mirai was later revealed to have been used during the DDoS attacks against Rutgers University from 2014 to 2016, which left faculty and students on campus unable to access the outside Internet for several days at a time.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Additionally, a failure of the university's Central Authentication Service caused course registration and other services to become unavailable during critical times in the academic semester.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The university reportedly spent $300,000 in consultation and increased the cyber-security budget of the university by $1 million in response to these attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The university cited the attacks among its reasons for the increase in tuition and fees for the 2015–2016 school year.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] A person under the alias "exfocus" claimed responsibility for the attacks, stating in a Reddit AMA on the */r/Rutgers* subreddit that the user was a student at the school and the DDoS attacks were motivated by frustrations with the university's bus system.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The same user later claimed in an interview with a New Jersey–based blogger that they had lied about being affiliated with the university and that the attacks were being funded by an anonymous client.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Security researcher Brian Krebs later alleged the user was indeed a student at Rutgers University and that the latter interview was given in an attempt to distract investigators.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Staff at Deep Learning Security observed the steady growth of Mirai botnets before and after the 21 October attack.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Mirai has also been used in an attack on Liberia's Internet infrastructure in November 2016.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] According to computer security expert Kevin Beaumont, the attack appears to have originated from the actor which also attacked Dyn.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Its DDoS attacks were also notable in Brazil, Taiwan, Costa Rica and India.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] At the end of November 2016, approximately 900,000 routers, from Deutsche Telekom and produced by Arcadyan, were crashed due to failed TR-064 exploitation attempts by a variant of Mirai, which resulted in Internet connectivity problems for the users of these devices.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] While TalkTalk later patched their routers, a new variant of Mirai was discovered in TalkTalk routers.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] A British man suspected of being behind the attack was arrested at Luton Airport, according to the BBC.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On January 17, 2017, computer security journalist Brian Krebs posted an article on his blog, Krebs on Security, where he disclosed the name of the person who he believed to have written the malware.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Krebs stated that the likely real-life identity of Anna-senpai (named after Anna Nishikinomiya, a character from *Shimoneta*), the author of Mirai, was actually an Indian-American Paras Jha, the owner of a DDoS mitigation service company ProTraf Solutions and a student of Rutgers University.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] In an update to the original article, Paras Jha responded to Krebs and denied having written Mirai.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The FBI was reported to have questioned Jha on his involvement in the October 2016 Dyn cyberattack.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On December 13, 2017, Paras Jha, Josiah White, and Dalton Norman entered a guilty plea to crimes related to the Mirai botnet.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] The trio assisted the government with other cybersecurity investigations, and were sentenced to probation and community service without imprisonment.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] On October 26th, 2018, Jha was ordered to pay $8.6 million in restitution and was sentenced to six months of home incarceration by the United States District Court for the District of New Jersey for the attack on Rutgers university.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Daniel Kaye, 29, also known as alias "BestBuy", "Popopret" or "Spiderman", has been accused of "using an infected network of computers known as the Mirai botnet to attack and blackmail Lloyds Banking Group and Barclays banks," according to the NCA.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] He has been extradited from Germany to the UK according to the same report.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] Kaye has also pleaded guilty in court on hijacking more than 900,000 routers from the network of Deutsche Telekom.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] District Court in Anchorage, followed by the arrest and trial of the suspect.
[src:iot-security-deep/mirai-malware] American electronic musician and composer James Ferraro's 2018 album *Four Pieces for Mirai* references Mirai in its ongoing narrative.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] An **over-the-air update** (or **OTA update**), also known as **over-the-air programming** (or **OTA programming**), is an update to an operating system, or to firmware for an embedded system, that is delivered through a wireless network, such as Wi-Fi or a cellular network.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] These systems include mobile phones, tablets, set-top boxes, cars and telecommunications equipment.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] OTA updates for cars and internet of things devices can also be called **firmware over-the-air** (**FOTA**).
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Various components may be updated OTA, including the device's operating system, applications, configuration settings, or parameters like encryption keys.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] The term *over-the-air update* applies to embedded systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Before OTA updates, embedded devices could only be flashed through direct physical access (with a JTAG) or wired connections (usually through USB or a serial port).
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] It is also used for mobile devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Over-the-air delivery may allow updates to be distributed at larger scales, reduce the cost of delivering updates, or increase the rate of adoption of these updates.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] The distributor of these updates can decide whether users are allowed to decline these updates, and may choose to disable certain features on end-user devices until an update is applied.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Users may be unable to revert an update after it is installed.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] OTA updates are designed to be as small as possible in order to minimize energy consumption, network usage, and storage space.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] This is achieved by only transferring the differences between the old firmware and the new firmware, rather than transmitting the entire firmware.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] A delta of the old and new firmware is produced through a process called diffing; then, the delta file is distributed to the end-device, which uses the delta file to update itself.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] On smartphones, tablets, and other devices, an over-the-air update is a firmware or operating system update that is downloaded by the device over the internet.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Previously, users had to connect these devices to a computer over USB to perform an update.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] These updates may add features, patch security vulnerabilities, or fix software bugs.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] The two main mobile operating systems are iOS and Android.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] iOS gained support for over-the-air updates in iOS 5. iOS updates are distributed exclusively by Apple, resulting in wide availability and relatively high adoption rates.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Major iOS releases are usually installed on 60%–70% of iPhones within a few months of release.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Android OTA updates are device-dependent, and are not distributed by Google but by device manufacturers and sometimes wireless carriers.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] This has led to inconsistent availability of updates, and to Android fragmentation.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] In the past, fragmentation increased the complexity of developing third-party apps for Android due to inconsistent availability of the latest software frameworks on users' phones, and led to security concerns due to delays in the distribution of security updates.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Project Mainline significantly lowers the role of middlemen in delivering OTA updates.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Since Android 8.0, Android OTA updates follow an A/B partition scheme, in which an update is installed to a second ("B") partition in the background, and the phone switches to that partition the next time it is rebooted, reducing the time taken to install updates.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Windows Phone OTA updates were usually distributed by OEMs such as Nokia, and sometimes wireless carriers.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] OTA updates for Windows Phone devices labelled Microsoft Mobile were usually distributed by Microsoft.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Cars can support OTA updates to their in-car entertainment system, navigation map, telematic control unit, or their electronic control units (the onboard computers responsible for most of the car's operation).
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] In cars, the telematic control unit is in charge of downloading and installing updates, and OTA updates are downloaded through cellular networks, like smartphones.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Cars cannot be driven while an OTA update is being installed.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Before an update, the car checks that the update is genuine, and after the update completes, it verifies the integrity of all affected systems.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] In the past, Volkswagen had to recall 11 million vehicles to fix an issue with its cars' emissions control software, and other manufacturers have instituted recalls due to software bugs affecting the brakes, or the airbags, requiring all affected customers to travel to dealership to receive updates.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] OTA updates would have removed the need to go through dealerships, leading to lower warranty costs for manufacturers and lower downtime for customers.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] OTA updates also allow manufacturers to deploy potential new features and bug fixes more quickly, making their cars more competitive in the market, and resulting in an increased pace of product improvements for consumers.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] For example, OTA updates can deliver improvements to a car's driver assistance systems and improve the car's safety.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] However, OTA updates can also present a new attack vector for hackers, since security vulnerabilities in the update process could be used by hackers to remotely take control of cars.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Hackers have discovered such vulnerabilities in the past, and many car manufacturers have responded by instituting vulnerability disclosure programs (a.k.a. bug bounty programs).
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Attack vectors specific to OTA updates include "spoofing, tampering, repudiation [attacks], information leakage, denial-of-service," replay attacks, and privilege escalation attacks.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] Sensor nodes are often located in places that are either remote or difficult to access.
[src:iot-security-deep/over-the-air-update] As an example, Libelium has implemented an OTA programming system for Zigbee WSN devices.
